    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i noticed my blueberry bushes have been getting these weird yellow leaves lately. the veins are still green but the rest of the leaf is turning pale. i've been watering them a lot, so i'm thinking maybe it's a soil issue? can you explain how the pH level actually affects how much iron the plant can take up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellow leaves on your blueberry bushes could be a sign of nutrient deficiency, with iron being a common culprit. Iron deficiency often causes a yellow or pale color on the upper side of the leaves, as you've described. The pH level can affect how much iron your blueberries can absorb, as blueberries require acidic to neutral soil pH levels (5.5-6.5). A pH level above 6.5 can lead to iron leaching, reducing the soil's iron availability and causing deficiency.",
      "source": "target",
