    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the info. so if the pH is too high, is the iron actually gone from the soil entirely, or is it just like... stuck? it's hard to get my head around how it can be there but the plant just can't grab it. it feels like something is blocking it or preventing it from working.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Iron is not completely removed from the soil when the pH increases, but it's released from the soil's anion exchange sites and becomes less available to plants. Think of it like the iron \"melts\" and becomes more mobile, but still present in the soil. The plant can't directly \"grab\" the iron, but the increased pH might reduce its mobilization, making it less accessible to your blueberries.",
      "source": "target",
